snippet.textDisplay:
Sorry Thiem but you don't have the mental power to beat Djokovic. And don't forget Djokovic didn't have the best day. Thiem has a lot of holes in his game: inconsistent first serve (he couldn't put pressure on Djokovic from the start), hit the balls too flat and as a result have a lot of unforced errors, when at net he doesn't know what to do with the ball, bad overheads and on top of these he is mentally weak.
Personally I don't like Djokovic's game as he just steals points instead of creating them. The only player that can beat Djokovic in grand slams is Wawrinka who has the power and consistency to destroy Djokovic on any surface. Unfortunately, Wawrinka really disappointed me in the game with Zverev.

Personally I don't like Djokovic's game as he just steals points instead of creating them. The only player that can beat Djokovic in grand slams is Wawrinka who has the power and consistency to destroy Djokovic on any surface. Unfortunately, Wawrinka really disappointed me in the game with Zverev.

snippet.textDisplay:
The good news is, today's match proved that Nole is not invincible. The 2nd and 3rd set, Thiem outhit Novak. 4th and 5th set, he tried to outhit him again in vain. But Novak had mixed things up beautifully! By shortening points, going up to the net, taking more risks. Thiems lack of versatility and concrete 'B' game did him in.

Novak strategy: Break the opponent down. Constantly pressurizing them, with his immaculate depth off both flanks There are only 3 people currently on tour, who can 'potentially' beat him over 5 sets, when he's playing like this:
1. Stan-imal mode: Pummel winners from obscene angles over 5 sets. Next to impossible task actually.

2. A prime Federer: Consistent attack + 'Neo' backhand + constant variation (2011 FO semis is a good example). Unfortunately, we'll likely not see that Federer again.

3. Rafa at French Open: No comment needed.
